In article <33gie5$i5a@herald.indirect.com>, johnk@bud.indirect.com (John Kuslich) writes:
|> I have written a program WPcrak which finds Wordperfect passwords for 
|> Wordperfect thru version 5.2.
|> 
|> This program implements a known plaintext attack against a well known 
|> weakness of the Wordperfect encryption algorithm.  The program uses a 
|> "reference file" which contains the same base font and printer setup as 
|> the encrypted file (usually this is available to a legitimate user) to 
|> determine the file password.
|> 
|> Of the thousands of copies in use, I have only had one validated 
|> complaint that the program would not automatically extract the exact 
|> password.  In this case the password was extracted by manually viewing 
|> the program output screen. One other case is pending ( I have not yet 
|> seen the files). 
|> 
|> I am wondering if there are any closet cryptographers out there who would 
|> be interested in helping me test the program and establish some data 
|> concerning reliability. I could possibly offer incentives.
|> 
|> E-mail me at:
|> 
|> johnk@indirect.com

Sure, I am interested.
